# 1\. Executive Summary

Deutsche Bank's current approach to observability is fragmented, tool-focused, and suffers from a lack of collaboration and data sharing across technical teams. This results in a "culture of secrecy" that hinders the full benefits of observability from being realized. Our vision is to establish a consistent, enterprise-wide observability strategy that addresses these challenges without mandating significant tooling changes, leveraging existing tools and augmenting them with a unifying layer. We aim to enhance incident management, optimize costs, improve security of observability data, and meet regulatory demands. The strategy will improve business impact analysis, event correlation, root cause analysis, end-to-end monitoring, and reduce Mean Time to Detect (MTTD) and Mean Time to Resolve (MTTR).

For Capacity Management, the current BMC TSCO solution faces an end-of-life in Q1 2027 and a complex, costly migration path to its replacement, BHCO. This strategy outlines options to address this impending challenge, including evaluating market alternatives and considering an in-house solution.

The 2026 Book of Work outlines specific initiatives and deliverables across various architectural facets (AP Arch Facet), focusing on strategic product replacements, platform decommissioning, workflow automation, and compliance adherence to achieve the defined observability and capacity management goals.

# 2\. Observability Strategy

## 2.1. Problem Statement

-   **Tool-Focused Approach:**Lack of key observability principles and recognition of observability as a distributed challenge. The Bank has a large and complex IT environment with numerous disconnected monitoring and observability tools leading to siloed telemetry, logs, and events.
-   **Data Silos and Secrecy:**Technical teams are reluctant to share data, hindering a holistic view of service performance and integrity. Duplicated data and inconsistent IT service management processes inhibit full-stack observability.
-   **Lack of Unified View:**No "Single Pane of Glass" for monitoring, with approximately 40 interfaces to ServiceNow incident API. Operations teams source data independently from various silos.
-   **Inconsistent Data:**Impacts the ability to quickly identify root causes in major incidents.
-   **Limited AIOps:**Not possible due to inconsistent and consolidated data, and limited implementation of predictive monitoring through AI capabilities or anomaly detection.
-   **Operational Management:**Still largely monitoring-driven, detecting pre-defined problems rather than predicting future issues.

## 2.2. Observability Vision

-   **Consistent Strategy:**Provide a strategy that acknowledges no single tool can meet all use cases. Define, at a high level, how cohesive monitoring and observability can be achieved in support of standardized ITSM processes.
-   **Data Sharing:**Vital for enterprise-wide observability requirements. Modern observability solutions with correct telemetry data will not only detect problems but also show why and potentially when they might happen.
-   **Tooling Flexibility:**Avoid mandating significant changes at the tooling level, recognizing the impracticality and cost of replacing all existing tools. The intention is to leverage existing tools and augment them with a unifying layer.
-   **Key Objectives:**
    -   Cost optimization of observability.
    -   Clear improvement in incident processes.
    -   Enhanced security of observability data.
    -   Meeting regulator demand for observability system characteristics.
    -   Enhance business impact analysis based on Service Level Objectives (SLOs) and automated indicators (SLIs).
    -   Enhance event correlation and root cause analysis (RCA).
    -   Enhance end-to-end monitoring and cross-team collaboration.
    -   Reduce Mean Time to Detect (MTTD) and Mean Time to Resolve (MTTR).
    -   Support standardization of ITSM processes for enhanced workflow automation and closer collaboration.

2.3. Interim State (2026)

The interim state focuses on introducing a common data collection capability and data pipeline to reduce data complexity and accelerate the journey to AIOps. This involves integrating existing monitoring tools into a unified framework.

-   **Key Initiatives:**
    -   Rollout New Relic to Hybrid Cloud.
    -   Setup the 'Event Pipeline'.
    -   Define Event Standards & Best Practices.
    -   Update Event Management Process and Governance.
    -   Integrate GTI Solutions and TDI Apps to the Event Pipeline.
    -   Integrate Events to an Event Single Pane of Glass.
    -   **Book of Work Initiatives (2026):**
        -   **Observability - Strategic Product on Hybrid Cloud:**Replacement of Nimsoft & NRI, including Telemetry Data Pipelines, OTEL Agent R&D, ITRS Analytics for dependency, Geneos 7 contract renewal with ITRS, and NRI replacement strategy.
        -   **Decommissioning/Maintenance of Existing Platforms:**Efforts on dbMac/SSO, Apptio Chargeback Optimization, technical approach to license consumption controls, automated maintenance requests for Nimsoft and Netcool.
        -   **Automation Platforms Audit Deliverables:**Remediation of Group Audit findings, database migration from Elasticsearch v7.x to V8.x and V9.x, Jenkins version updates and pipeline maintenance, Java Patching compliance.
-   **Architectural Changes:**Introduction of a common data pipeline for event and telemetry data, alongside a common services data model (CSDM). All events will be consolidated into a single platform, improving event correlation for incident detection and enabling faster root cause analysis. This is expected to lead to reduced incidents and shorter outages. The Telemetry Pipeline Service will ingest, cleanse, transform, and route data.

2.4. Target State

The target state envisions an enterprise-wide, open standards-driven observability framework utilizing a Telemetry Pipeline and AIOps.

-   **Core Components:**
    -   **Telemetry Pipeline & AIOps:**An enabler for AIOps, with CSDM-driven topology correlation and Agentic AI integrations with downstream observability platforms.
    -   **Open Telemetry Collection:**Standardized collection from various sources (Application, Public Cloud, Private Cloud, Platform, Infrastructure). This includes Telemetry Collection Services responsible for secure collection of MELT data (Metrics, Events, Logs, Traces). Existing tools like Syslog, SNMP, gRPC, OTLP, and agents will feed into this.
    -   **Message Bus:**A distributed, highly available publish-subscribe mechanism (e.g., Kafka) for data transit from collection services to the pipeline, optimized for real-time processing.
    -   **Telemetry Pipeline Service:**Ingests, cleanses (filters, redacts, corrects, removes duplicates), transforms (normalizes, extracts, enriches), and routes data to the Event Management System and Centralized Telemetry Storage.
    -   **Telemetry Data Store:**Must support all MELT data types, ingest at high speed, index large volumes, store multiple copies, be highly available, support fast querying, use compression, support encryption at rest, handle sensitive data, and have IDAM controls.
    -   **Event Management Service:**Performs event correlation and root cause analysis (RCA) by analyzing events (alerts, logs, metrics) across systems to identify patterns and relationships, reducing noise and identifying actual problems. It also handles response selection, ranging from archiving to automated actions (e.g., incident tickets).
    -   **Observability Services:**Provides in-depth visibility into performance and availability across applications, infrastructure, and networks from all telemetry sources, facilitating detection of bottlenecks, resource constraints, and other problems. This includes dashboards for real-time analysis, bottleneck detection, topology-based relationship representation, and automated event creation from anomalies.
    -   **Pipeline Prep and Process:**Data ingestion and initial processing.
    -   **AIOps & Semantic Search Repository:**Central components for intelligent analysis, correlation, and search.
    -   **Intelligent Pipeline Routing & Open Telemetry Routing:**Directs data to consumers based on needs.
-   **Benefits:**
    -   Single Pane of Glass for managing, diagnosing, and troubleshooting incidents (Agentic AI).
    -   Predictive and preventative incident capabilities.
    -   Rapid understanding of "Service & Business Impact" (Blast Radius).
    -   Reduced incidents and improved Mean Time To Resolve (MTTR).
    -   Reduced agent deployment and maintenance.
    -   Instant view for incident management, accelerating incident resolution.
    -   Simplification of the monitoring agent estate, leading to reduced CPU consumption and lower license costs.
    -   Increased asset utilization through accurate usage information and forecasting.
    -   Event Storm Reduction via AI analysis, improving incident response.
    -   Front-to-back view of system state for approved consumers and reliable application management.
    -   Automated filtering and redaction of logs, significantly reducing data leakage risk.

## 2.5. Data Architecture (Key Principles)

-   **Data Entities:**Observability relies on Metrics, Events, Logs, and Traces (MELT). These provide quantifiable measurements, discrete actions, chronological records, and end-to-end request flows, respectively.
-   **Data Relationships:**Defines how Configuration Items (CI) relate to MELT data, e.g., CI to Event (one-to-one), CI to Metric (one-to-many), CI to Log (one-to-one), CI to Trace (many-to-one).
-   **Data Attributes:**Standardized attributes for Metrics (Timestamp, CI Name, Metric Name, Value), Events (Timestamp, Event Message, Severity), and Logs (Timestamp, Message/Payload, Log level/Severity). Traces include Trace ID, Span Identifier, Root span, Parent-Child Relationships, and key-value pairs.
-   **Data Lifecycle Management:**Focuses on managing telemetry data from generation to deletion, including collection, processing, enrichment, storage, visualization, retention, and archival.
-   **Data Governance:**Ensures visibility of data behavior, policy enforcement, and issue tracing, covering availability, integrity, usability, and security. This includes data retention policies for compliance and business needs.
-   **Data Security and Privacy:**Employs encryption (at rest, in use, in transit, end-to-end) and follows privacy/security best practices for sharing data. Rules-based access controls (RBAC), secure channels, and audit trails are essential.
-   **Data Quality:**Critical for preventing false alerts and missed incidents. Key dimensions include accuracy, completeness, and timeliness.

# 3\. Capacity Management Strategy

## 3.1. Current State

-   **BMC TSCO:**Currently the Capacity Management solution.
-   **EOL Date:**BMC TSCO reaches End-of-Life in Q1 2027.
-   **Replacement:**To be replaced by BMC BHCO.
-   **Hybrid Cloud Integration:**Future demand from Hybrid Cloud can technically be integrated into TSCO.

## 3.2. Challenges

-   **Migration Complexity:**No simple migration path to BHCO; it's a transformation.
-   **Cost:**Approximately 3 million to transform to BHCO.
-   **License Costs:**Risk of increased license costs.
-   **Funding:**No approved IG Funding for 2026.

## 3.3. Strategic Options

-   **Build Our Own Solution:**
    -   **Pros:**Lower build cost (with limited requirements), tailored to DB's needs, avoids vendor lock-in.
    -   **Cons:**Bank retains supportability, likely functional limitations, challenging timeline management.
-   **Transform to BMC Alternative (BHCO):**
    -   **Pros:**Vendor-supported professional services, similar look and feel to current tools, maintains current capabilities.
    -   **Cons:**High cost (3m) difficult to justify against benefit, vendor behavior not challenged, migration is a significant transformation.
-   **Run TSCO (Unsupported):**
    -   **Pros:**Zero cost due to perpetual licenses, low risk to business services.
    -   **Cons:**Requires risk acceptance for running in production without support.
-   **Go to Market (RFI & RFP):**
    -   **Pros:**Opportunity to re-evaluate the market for enhanced capabilities at lower cost.
    -   **Cons:**Unlikely to complete RFI, RFP, and deployment within the 14-month timeframe, limited solutions in the marketplace (IBM and Dynatrace already discounted).

3.4. Timelines and Milestones - Capacity Management

The strategy for Capacity Management will be agreed upon by Q3 2026, with secure funding by Q4 2026 and implementation of a strategic solution expected to deliver a solution by Q3 2027, before TSCO goes out of support in Q4 2027.

-   **2026 Book of Work Initiatives:**
    -   **Capacity Management - Strategic Tool in Place March 2027:**This includes TSCO replacement due to EOL, funding and technical approach decisions, SDLC/NAR enablement, deployment, and eventual decommissioning of TSCO. Process improvements for Capacity Management are also planned.

# 4\. Hybrid Cloud Readiness

-   **VMs:**Traditional VMs will be used.
-   **Nimsoft Agents:**To be deployed with VMs.
-   **dbPerfmon:**Available to observe Performance timeseries metrics.
-   **Monitoring & Notification:**Via Netcool.
-   **2026 Book of Work Initiatives:**
    -   **Observability - Strategic Product On Hybrid Cloud: Replacement Nimsoft & NRI:**Focus on Private Cloud Observability and On-prem Observability, including NRIA deployment strategies, pipeline for config management and agent upgrade, migration of policies using Terraform, and addressing data privacy obligations for NR deployment.
    -   **New Relic Initiatives:**Sub-account cost monitoring/management, MS Teams & NR Integration, Scorecard, Codestream IDE plugin, New Relic CLI for resource management, and network proxy remediation to avoid DLP.
    -   **Hybrid Cloud Control Plane Alignment:**Work focuses on Oracle Apex Upgrade, Net Apps Workflow Onboarding, ECS Workflow Onboarding, and implementing the new Control Workbench Prioritization Model
